          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Implement connection pooling, async I/O, and load balancing to handle high traffic. Monitor resource usage to scale horizontally as needed."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "h2",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Error Handling and Resilience"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Build robust error handling to maintain service availability. Check HTTP status codes: 429 indicates rate limiting—implement exponential backoff; 500 suggests server issues—trigger alerts and fallbacks. Use circuit breakers to isolate failures, and log detailed error messages for debugging. For network timeouts, set reasonable timeouts (e.g., 30 seconds) and retry with jitter to avoid thundering herd problems."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "h2",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Monitoring and Maintenance"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Establish comprehensive monitoring to track API health and performance. Log metrics such as request latency, error rates, and token usage. Integrate with tools like Prometheus or Datadog for real-time dashboards and alerts. Regularly review API versioning and update SDKs to incorporate improvements. Conduct periodic load tests to validate scalability and adjust configurations proactively."
          }
        ]
